subSection.paragraph:
The subtribe Lychnophorinae consists of ca. 120 species (19 genera) occurring mostly in the Brazilian Central Plateau in the Cerrado domain, in cerrado s.s. and campos rupestres (highland rocky fields) physiognomies. Plants of this subtribe are usually shrubs or treelets that display a thick indumentum covering leaves and/or stems, likely an efficient protection against fire and herbivory. The capitula are frequently aggregated into a secondary order inflorescence associated to a certain degree of reduction (i.e., syncephalia) (
Loeuille et al. 2019
).

Morphological features of the specimens were analyzed with an 8–40 × magnification stereomicroscope. Measurements of only fully mature structures were made using a digital caliper rule and optical graticule attached to the microscope. The measurements of capitula, corollas, anthers, and styles were made from dried specimens, rehydrated for microscopic examination of its floral parts, and the leaves were measured using dry material. Terminology follows Hickey (1973) for leaf shape and Harris & Harris (2001) for general morphology. The distribution map was produced in QGIS version 3.12 ( QGIS Development Team 2020 ). Geographic coordinates were obtained from herbarium specimens. The conservation status for each species was determined according to the IUCN criteria and method ( IUCN 2012 , 2019 ). We used the GeoCAT tool (
Bachman et al. 2011
) to estimate Extent of Occurrence (EOO) and Area of Occupancy (AOO, cell size of 2 km 2 ).
